text:
Neptune Ave., south side, between Shell Road and West 6th Street. A view of the Oceanic Hotel built in 1829, and subsequently rebuilt at a latter date. It is no longer standing according to the maps of 1929. In 1894 it was the property of A. Lindermann. (Coney Island).

About 1900.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

622 Neptune Ave., south side, east of West 8th Street. To the right of No. 622, was the Coney Island House, which was moved to its present location in 1921. The building to the extreme right, is also a part of the same hotel. It is now "The Harvest," kept by one Levine.

December 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(1)
Neptune Ave., north side, at west 8th Street, showing a group of shacks and the blacksmith shop of James Maloney which will be demolished at some date subsequent to 1929, as they are in the way of the proposed West 8th Street.
August 1924.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2)
The same, showing at the right, the Atlantic Baking Co., formerly known as the Segallis Bakery, on the east side of Shell Road north of Neptune Ave.
October 1928.
Eugene L. Armbruster collection.

(1)
Neptune Ave., looking north, between West 12th and 8th Streets, showing an old bridge across Coney Island Creek. To the right and beyond it, are some oil storage tanks, and to the left directly opposite, is a 2-story brick building of the Brooklyn Borough Gas Co.

August 1924.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2)
The same, looking south from Canal Ave. To the right is an old abandoned railroad bridge east of the one shown in view No. 1.

November 1924.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
